{
  "card_id": "moving_average_convergence_divergence",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Moving Average Convergence Divergence",
  "aliases": [
    "5355 MACD",
    "5355 macd",
    "macd",
    "MACD",
    "moving average convergence divergence (macd)",
    "Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)"
  ],
  "school": "Indicator Based",
  "definition": "The Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD) is a momentum oscillator that subtracts a longer moving average from a shorter one to form the MACD line, with a signal line (moving average of the MACD line) and an optional histogram showing the difference. It measures trend strength and momentum, and is used to identify divergences (price vs. indicator moving oppositely) signaling potential reversals or continuations. Custom settings (e.g., 3,10,16 SMA) increase sensitivity for faster signals.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "The standard MACD line is calculated as the 12-period EMA minus the 26-period EMA; the signal line is a 9-period EMA (or SMA) of the MACD line.",
    "The histogram represents the distance between the MACD line and the signal line; it is positive when the MACD is above the signal line and negative when below.",
    "The zero line is crossed when the MACD line moves from negative to positive (or vice versa), corresponding to the 12-period EMA crossing above (or below) the 26-period EMA.",
    "A bullish divergence is identified when price prints a lower low while the MACD line or histogram prints a higher low.",
    "A bearish divergence is identified when price prints a higher high while the MACD line or histogram prints a lower high.",
    "A hidden bearish divergence occurs when price prints a lower high while the MACD line prints a higher high.",
    "An impulsive move is confirmed when the MACD line prints a clear higher high compared to its prior high; a lower high on MACD while price makes a higher high signals momentum divergence (weakness).",
    "Custom MACD settings (e.g., fast=3, slow=10, signal=16, all SMA, no histogram) provide faster divergence and momentum signals, and are often used with only the raw MACD line displayed.",
    "Peaks (MACD line above signal) indicate bullish momentum, valleys (MACD line below signal) indicate bearish momentum; the vertical distance reflects momentum strength.",
    "Crossovers: a MACD line crossing above the signal line is bullish, below is bearish; crossing above the zero line signals a bullish trend shift, below signals a bearish shift."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "MACD is used to gauge trend strength, identify momentum shifts, and spot potential reversals or continuations via divergences (bullish, bearish, hidden). Shorter-period custom settings (e.g., 3,10,16 SMA) provide faster signals suitable for day trading and scalping but increase false signals and should be confirmed with price action or market structure. Momentum confirmation (higher highs on MACD) validates impulsive moves; momentum divergence warns of weakness. Crossovers and zero-line crosses offer trend-following signals. It is often combined with support/resistance zones and failure tests for entry timing.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Relying solely on MACD signals without confirming with price action, market structure, or additional context.",
    "Assuming custom MACD settings are always superior without recognizing they produce more false signals.",
    "Relying on the histogram when using fast, sensitive settings (e.g., 3,10,16) as it hovers near zero and generates false signals.",
    "Trading pullbacks without confirming that the prior impulsive move had strong momentum (MACD higher high), or ignoring momentum divergence signals.",
    "Relying solely on standard MACD settings without considering custom settings for specific timeframes or strategies."
  ],
